Workers downed tools nearly two weeks ago, calling for a bigger increase, incentive bonuses and a late shift increase. JOHANNESBURG - The Gautrain has assured commuters that it will continue to provide limited services as the strike enters its eleventh day. Workers downed tools nearly two weeks ago, calling for a bigger increase, incentive bonuses and a late shift increase. The CCMA intervened on Monday with negotiations between holding company Bombela and the United National Transport Union (Untu). Talks have however deadlocked. Gautrain's Kes Naidoo: "A reduced service will certainly be available on 9 August. We encourage passengers to visit the Gautrain website for details of the contingency plan." Untu on Wednesday called on Gauteng Transport MEC Ismail Vadi to intervene. 